Here is the exact block, verbatim:

```js
// Line 66 — destructure from request body
const { transcript, photoBase64, mimeType, ... } = req.body

// Line 68
const sanitisedTranscript = sanitise(transcript)

// Line 70-72 — strip data URL prefix
const cleanBase64 = typeof photoBase64 === 'string'
  ? photoBase64.replace(/^data:[^;]+;base64,/, '')
  : null

// Line 74-90 — build content array
const content = []
if (cleanBase64) {
  content.push({
    type: 'image',
    source: {
      type:       'base64',
      media_type: mimeType || 'image/jpeg',
      data:       cleanBase64,
    },
  })
}
if (sanitisedTranscript) content.push({ type: 'text', text: sanitisedTranscript })

if (content.length === 0) { ... return 400 }

// Line 92 — passed to API
messages: [{ role: 'user', content }],
```

The construction logic is structurally correct. The one thing that can't be verified from this code alone is **what `photoBase64` actually contains when it arrives**. The `app.js` client does `.split(',')[1]` before sending, but the server also strips the prefix — so if the prefix is still present after both strips, the data URL format is non-standard.

The most useful next step is adding a temporary `console.error` log to see the actual value hitting the server. Drop this immediately after line 70:

```js
console.error('[analyze] photoBase64 prefix check:', typeof photoBase64 === 'string' ? photoBase64.slice(0, 50) : photoBase64)
```

That will print the first 50 chars of `photoBase64` as received — before stripping — in the Vercel function log. That single log will confirm or rule out the prefix theory definitively.

Shall I add that log, deploy, and then remove it once you've captured the output?

